chapter.verse:
Let gloom and deep darkness claim it.
Let clouds dwell upon it;
let the blackness of the day terrify it.

That night&emdash;let thick darkness seize it!
Let it not rejoice among the days of the year;
let it not come into the number of the months.

Let the stars of its dawn be dark;
let it hope for light, but have none,
nor see the eyelids of the morning,

His children are far from safety;
they are crushed in the gate,
and there is no one to deliver them.

For the arrows of the Almighty are in me;
my spirit drinks their poison;
the terrors of God are arrayed against me.

This would be my comfort;
I would even exult in pain unsparing,
for I have not denied the words of the Holy One.

Therefore I will not restrain my mouth;
I will speak in the anguish of my spirit;
I will complain in the bitterness of my soul.

if you are pure and upright,
surely then he will rouse himself for you
and restore your rightful habitation.

The earth is given into the hand of the wicked;
he covers the faces of its judges&emdash;
if it is not he, who then is it?

I loathe my life;
I will give free utterance to my complaint;
I will speak in the bitterness of my soul.

You renew your witnesses against me
and increase your vexation toward me;
you bring fresh troops against me.

But the eyes of the wicked will fail;
all way of escape will be lost to them,
and their hope is to breathe their last.

But I have understanding as well as you;
I am not inferior to you.
Who does not know such things as these?

I am a laughingstock to my friends;
I, who called to God and he answered me,
a just and blameless man, am a laughingstock.

You put my feet in the stocks
and watch all my paths;
you set a limit for the soles of my feet.

For there is hope for a tree,
if it be cut down, that it will sprout again,
and that its shoots will not cease.

so a man lies down and rises not again;
till the heavens are no more he will not awake
or be roused out of his sleep.

the waters wear away the stones;
the torrents wash away the soil of the earth;
so you destroy the hope of man.

and has lived in desolate cities,
in houses that none should inhabit,
which were ready to become heaps of ruins;

he will not depart from darkness;
the flame will dry up his shoots,
and by the breath of his mouth he will depart.

He has torn me in his wrath and hated me;
he has gnashed his teeth at me;
my adversary sharpens his eyes against me.

Men have gaped at me with their mouth;
they have struck me insolently on the cheek;
they mass themselves together against me.

I was at ease, and he broke me apart;
he seized me by the neck and dashed me to pieces;
he set me up as his target;

his archers surround me.
He slashes open my kidneys and does not spare;
he pours out my gall on the ground.

His troops come on together;
they have cast up their siege ramp against me
and encamp around my tent.

be afraid of the sword,
for wrath brings the punishment of the sword,
that you may know there is a judgment.

It is drawn forth and comes out of his body;
the glittering point comes out of his gallbladder;
terrors come upon him.

Utter darkness is laid up for his treasures;
a fire not fanned will devour him;
what is left in his tent will be consumed.

The clods of the valley are sweet to him;
all mankind follows after him,
and those who go before him are innumerable.

Behold, like wild donkeys in the desert
the poor go out to their toil, seeking game;
the wasteland yields food for their children.

From out of the city the dying groan,
and the soul of the wounded cries for help;
yet God charges no one with wrong.

The eye of the adulterer also waits for the twilight,
saying, No eye will see me;
and he veils his face.

In the dark they dig through houses;
by day they shut themselves up;
they do not know the light.

You say, Swift are they on the face of the waters;
their portion is cursed in the land;
no treader turns toward their vineyards.

The womb forgets them;
the worm finds them sweet;
they are no longer remembered,
so wickedness is broken like a tree.

They are exalted a little while, and then are gone;
they are brought low and gathered up like all others;
they are cut off like the heads of grain.

He opens shafts in a valley away from where anyone lives;
they are forgotten by travelers;
they hang in the air, far away from mankind; they swing to and fro.

On my right hand the rabble rise;
they push away my feet;
they cast up against me their ways of destruction.

They break up my path;
they promote my calamity;
they need no one to help them.

Terrors are turned upon me;
my honor is pursued as by the wind,
and my prosperity has passed away like a cloud.

because I stood in great fear of the multitude,
and the contempt of families terrified me,
so that I kept silence, and did not go out of doors&emdash;

  let thorns grow instead of wheat,
  and foul weeds instead of barley.


The words of Job are ended.

In a dream, in a vision of the night,
when deep sleep falls on men,
while they slumber on their beds,

and he is merciful to him, and says,
Deliver him from going down into the pit;
I have found a ransom;

then man prays to God, and he accepts him;
he sees his face with a shout of joy,
and he restores to man his righteousness.

In a moment they die;
at midnight the people are shaken and pass away,
and the mighty are taken away by no human hand.

When he is quiet, who can condemn?
When he hides his face, who can behold him,
whether it be a nation or a man?&emdash;

For he adds rebellion to his sin;
he claps his hands among us
and multiplies his words against God.

After it his voice roars;
he thunders with his majestic voice,
and he does not restrain the lightnings when his voice is heard.

The Almighty&emdash;we cannot find him;
he is great in power;
justice and abundant righteousness he will not violate.

Behold, Behemoth,
which I made as I made you;
he eats grass like an ox.
